{
  "masechta": "Bava Metzia",
  "daf": 19,
  "amud": "a",
  "macro_segments": [
    {
      "title": "Rabba bar Bar Chana's Lost Get: Identifying Marks and Recognition",
      "display_title": "Lost Get - Simanim",
      "timestamp": "01:35",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabba bar Bar Chana loses a get in the beis medrash and offers to identify it by simanim or by personal recognition",
          "display_title": "Rabba's Lost Get",
          "timestamp": "01:35"
        },
        {
          "title": "They return the get to him; uncertainty whether based on simanim being d'Oraisa or based on trustworthiness of his recognition as a talmid chacham",
          "display_title": "Simanim vs. Recognition",
          "timestamp": "02:56"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Get Found in Marketplace: Concerns About Dating and the Husband's Ability to Sell Fruit",
      "display_title": "Get Dating Concern",
      "timestamp": "06:12",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Braita: when husband admits the get fell from the wife, return it to her; when he denies it, return to neither",
          "display_title": "Braita on Get Return",
          "timestamp": "06:12"
        },
        {
          "title": "Concern about get dated Nisan but only given in Tishrei; husband sold fruit in between when he still had rights",
          "display_title": "Nisan-Tishrei Problem",
          "timestamp": "07:44"
        },
        {
          "title": "Wife claims property sold by husband was hers because divorce dated to Nisan; husband has no right to sell",
          "display_title": "Wife's Claim on Fruit",
          "timestamp": "08:39"
        },
        {
          "title": "Opinion: husband loses fruit rights once he decides to divorce; therefore no problem if get dated Nisan",
          "display_title": "Loses Rights on Intention",
          "timestamp": "09:42"
        },
        {
          "title": "Counterview: husband retains fruit rights until actual divorce; concern remains about earlier dating",
          "display_title": "Rights Until Divorce",
          "timestamp": "10:13"
        },
        {
          "title": "Solution: when wife tries to claim fruit, demand she prove when she actually received the get",
          "display_title": "Demand Proof of Receipt",
          "timestamp": "10:30"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Comparison to Lost Debt Documents: Why Gittin Can Be Returned But Shtar Chov Cannot",
      "display_title": "Gittin vs. Debt Docs",
      "timestamp": "11:41",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Question: why return a get when we do not return lost debt documents with liens, even when debtor admits?",
          "display_title": "Why Different Rules?",
          "timestamp": "11:41"
        },
        {
          "title": "Concern about debt documents: maybe written before money lent; creditor uses false lien dates to seize property",
          "display_title": "Debt Doc Concern",
          "timestamp": "12:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Proposal: return debt documents and demand proof of when loan occurred, similar to get case",
          "display_title": "Proof for Debt Docs?",
          "timestamp": "13:59"
        },
        {
          "title": "Distinction: people remember get was found and returned; will challenge its use for property claims",
          "display_title": "Get: Remembered Finding",
          "timestamp": "14:40"
        },
        {
          "title": "Debt document: if returned, creditor presumed to have done due diligence; buyers will not challenge liens",
          "display_title": "Debt: Assumed Kosher",
          "timestamp": "16:01"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Writ of Manumission (Shtar Shichrur): Similar Logic to the Get",
      "display_title": "Manumission Logic",
      "timestamp": "18:25",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Braita: when master admits document fell, give to slave; when he denies, give to neither",
          "display_title": "Master Admits/Denies",
          "timestamp": "18:25"
        },
        {
          "title": "Concern: document dated Nisan but given Tishrei; slave bought and owned property in between as slave",
          "display_title": "Slave's Property Gap",
          "timestamp": "19:02"
        },
        {
          "title": "Master sold slave's purchases; freed slave claims property back retroactive to Nisan",
          "display_title": "Retroactive Freedom Claim",
          "timestamp": "19:34"
        },
        {
          "title": "Opinion: freedom is absolute benefit; witnesses' signature frees slave immediately by zachin principle",
          "display_title": "Freedom as Benefit",
          "timestamp": "20:57"
        },
        {
          "title": "Counterview: freedom is not absolute benefit; cannot apply zachin; slave not freed until given",
          "display_title": "Not Absolute Benefit",
          "timestamp": "21:51"
        },
        {
          "title": "Solution: same as get—when slave claims property, demand proof of when freedom was received",
          "display_title": "Proof of Freedom Date",
          "timestamp": "22:59"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Will and Gift Documents (Deathbed Bequest vs. Healthy Person's Gift)",
      "display_title": "Will & Gift Docs",
      "timestamp": "23:56",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Mishna and braita on not returning will documents and gift documents without explicit instruction",
          "display_title": "Basic Rule on Docs",
          "timestamp": "23:56"
        },
        {
          "title": "Definition of dayatiki (will): instructions by dying person that property goes to someone upon death",
          "display_title": "What Is Dayatiki",
          "timestamp": "24:01"
        },
        {
          "title": "Definition of matana (gift by healthy person): transfers title today but benefit only after death",
          "display_title": "What Is Matana",
          "timestamp": "24:58"
        },
        {
          "title": "Why matana phrased as 'from today until after death': healthy person cannot convey after death",
          "display_title": "Title/Benefit Split",
          "timestamp": "25:28"
        },
        {
          "title": "Braita: even if both parties admit, do not return gift or will documents",
          "display_title": "Braita Restriction",
          "timestamp": "28:00"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Why Deathbed Bequests Can Be Returned but Healthy Gifts Cannot",
      "display_title": "Deathbed vs. Healthy",
      "timestamp": "30:08",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Deathbed bequest is retractable; later document always supersedes earlier one",
          "display_title": "Retractable Nature",
          "timestamp": "30:08"
        },
        {
          "title": "Even if earlier deathbed document never given, later deathbed document to different person supersedes it",
          "display_title": "Later Supersedes Earlier",
          "timestamp": "31:33"
        },
        {
          "title": "Healthy person's gift is final; earlier gift takes precedence over later gift",
          "display_title": "Gift Is Final",
          "timestamp": "33:47"
        },
        {
          "title": "Scenario: document dated January for Reuven never given; February gift to Shimon given; now regret",
          "display_title": "Two-Gift Scenario",
          "timestamp": "34:09"
        },
        {
          "title": "Concern: giver will falsely claim January document was given; Reuven will win by earlier date",
          "display_title": "False Claim Risk",
          "timestamp": "37:29"
        },
        {
          "title": "For healthy gift, even if both admit, do not return because earlier document date can be exploited",
          "display_title": "Exploit Risk",
          "timestamp": "38:13"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Rav Zvid's Distinction: Deathbed Bequest Returned Only If Giver Alive",
      "display_title": "Alive vs. Dead Giver",
      "timestamp": "40:44",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Both mishna and braita speak of deathbed bequest but reach opposite conclusions",
          "display_title": "Apparent Contradiction",
          "timestamp": "40:44"
        },
        {
          "title": "Both sources address deathbed bequests but differ on whether giver is still alive or deceased",
          "display_title": "Key Difference",
          "timestamp": "41:13"
        },
        {
          "title": "When giver still alive: if he later gives to another, that gift supersedes and Shimon is protected",
          "display_title": "Alive: Later Wins",
          "timestamp": "41:36"
        },
        {
          "title": "When giver deceased, only son can gift; if son gives to Shimon, it does not supersede father's bequest",
          "display_title": "Dead: Son Can't Override",
          "timestamp": "42:19"
        },
        {
          "title": "Concern: son falsely claims father gave to Reuven; takes it from Shimon; splits proceeds with Reuven",
          "display_title": "Fraud Scenario",
          "timestamp": "45:50"
        },
        {
          "title": "Therefore do not return bequest if giver dead; tell son to give new document if he truly owes Reuven",
          "display_title": "No Return if Dead",
          "timestamp": "46:59"
        },
        {
          "title": "If son's current gift to Reuven is dated today and Shimon's is dated earlier, Shimon's still wins",
          "display_title": "Son's Later Doc",
          "timestamp": "48:07"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
